Vector in Java

Vector is a class in Java that implements the List interface, similar to ArrayList.

It is based on a dynamic array, meaning it can grow and shrink automatically.

Key Difference from ArrayList

👉 The main difference:

Vector is synchronized (thread-safe)
ArrayList is not synchronized

This means:

Vector is safe to use in multi-threaded environments
but it is slower because of synchronization
Creating a Vector
import java.util.Vector;

Vector<String> vector = new Vector<>();
Common Methods
Adding elements
vector.add("Apple");
vector.addElement("Banana"); // older method
Accessing elements
vector.get(0);
vector.firstElement();
vector.lastElement();
Updating elements
vector.set(1, "Mango");
Removing elements
vector.remove(0);
vector.removeElement("Apple");
vector.clear();
Size
vector.size();
Legacy Methods (Old Style)

Vector also has older methods (from early Java):

addElement()
elementAt()
removeElement()

👉 Today we usually use modern methods like add(), get(), remove()

When to use Vector?

Use Vector when:

you need thread safety
multiple threads access the same list
When NOT to use

Avoid Vector when:

you don’t need synchronization
performance is important

👉 In most cases, ArrayList is preferred.

Vector vs ArrayList
Feature	Vector	ArrayList
Thread-safe	✅	❌
Performance	Slower	Faster
Usage	Rare today	Very common
Summary
Vector is a dynamic array like ArrayList
it is thread-safe
slower due to synchronization
mostly replaced by ArrayList in modern Java
